<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08137g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08137g">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08137g"> 137(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ostreaculture / Burren (Mayo) / French beds &mdash; seeds from / Arklow</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Irish Oyster Beds / Seanad Wants Them Developed</b> <br> The Seanad adopted a resolution by Dr. Sigerson requesting the Government that as Ireland is favourably situated for purposes of <mark>ostreaculture</mark>, and that many beds of oysters have been formed around her coasts <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> to <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> report on the best methods of protecting, improving, and extending them. Mr Barrington, who seconded the motion, contrasted the Whistable beds <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> with those of <mark>Burren, Co. Mayo</mark>, where a natural bed of seven miles could not be utilised to supply the Dublin market.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Sir T. H. G. Esmonde mentioned that <mark>the seeds to start the famous French beds</mark>, which now earned great profits, had been taken </mark>from Arklow</mark>. <small> <a name="II7feb24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#II7feb24"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (7 February 1924) 4/2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Arklow is a seaport and market town of the county Wicklow, Ireland. There are oyster beds on the coast but the produce requires to be freed from a peculiar flavour by the purer waters of the Welsh and English coast before it is fit for food. </mm> </dd></dl>
